info.other: My estimate at the description translation[;] Very slight central ridge on blade, a few prominent and neat ridges on reverse[;] Upper parts flattened and flanked by trace hollows, not symmetrical[;] Stop crests flattened, not regular[;] Flange crests rounded where intact.[;] blade sides are double faceted[;] One septum floor is more rounded than the other, diffuse ber. at top of septum, even.  Septum end with one definite short rib, on reverse with prominent one to left – possible other(s), small possible hollow in one septum end[;] Pronounced hammering of blade faces, less prominent on one side, no definite edge bevel, a bit diffuse on reverse face[;] Some gulfs across W. e. may be […] strong of eg. ft. only evidence between loop stumps – […] removed evidence on intact sides.[;] blade edge all lost through […] damage – possible previous damage also[;] most of […] pale green, but one tip grey-green – pres. Just patina flaked[;] pronounced loop stumps now just corroded lumps[;] most of butt lost[;] little parts rear intact[;] parts of flange crests little cover damage[;] crevice in palstave below one stop – ridge in center damaged.

bl.e. all lost through [...] dam. - pass. previous dam. else; i most of lnrak pale green, but one tip grey-green - pres. just p. flaked; pronounced loop stumps now just corroded lumps; most of butt lost. little pieces war intact; parts of fg. crests [inserted word not visible] covr - dam.; crevice in p. below one stop - pids in cent dam.

info.other:
This card had three "Width" measurements labeled as "edge," "middle," and "butt." The "edge" measurement has been entered into the "Edge" field, but the "middle" and "butt" measurements had to be separated in the "Width" field.

"England Middlesex" on the card was parenthesized and struck through. In addition, a word that could be "Thomas" was parenthesized and scribbled through at a later date. "Ponders End" was underlined in the same pen that wrote "Greater London."

The description "Well preserved" was written in what is technically "Composition" space, but quite removed from the heading, so it has been entered into the "Description" field instead. It may have been intended as part of the "Surface" description, but this is unclear.

info.site: england[;]gloucestershire[;]dudbridge (1 mile from stroud)[;]dudbridge mills[;]found in a sewerage excavation in an orchard, embedded in lias clay, about 10 feet from the surface, at some time before the opening of the stroud museum.
info.associations: "In this particular bronze axe some fragments of wood were found, but unfortunately the [navey?] (the finder) brushed these out."
info.description: "It is a remarkably well-formed weapon. The edge is quite sharp, which may be accounted for by the fact of its having been enclosed in matrix of clay."[;]From the sketch, there appears to be three ridges down the face of the blade; prominent stop-ridge; and chips out of the cutting edge at the end nearer the loop, and from the edges of one of the side flanges.
info.collection: ?Stroud Museum or in Private hands? But see other side.
info.remarks: For all known particulars, see other side.[;]From an old (undated, but 1910 or 1911) cutting from a Stroud newspaper, sent to the British Museum in January 1936 by the curator of Stroud Museum, to whom the cutting has been returned. The description and particulars on the face of this card are from the same cutting:[;]"We are indebted to Mr. John Bezant, specialist in the antique, of George Street, Stroud, for permission to illustrate a Bronze Celt or Battle Axe, recently found in a sewerage excavation in an orchard near Dudbridge Mills. The navey who found the ancient weapon was well advised in taking it to Mr. Brazant, because in addition to being a keen antiquariest, he is also anxious to witness the opening of the long-promised museum in Stroud, and although he has been made a valuable offer for this find, he has formed the resolution not to part with it until he has received assurance that it will eventually come to the local Museum...[;]A find would probably be there (i.e. at Dudbridge), as at Ryeford, as Celtic (sic) people who lived in Gloucestershire would naturally when moving from one hilly district to another select the most suitable spots in marshy lowlands for passing on to firmer ground." Here follows a dissertation on varieties of Celts from "Arms and Armour", and irrelevant remarks about Stone, Bronze, and Iron Ages, Romans, Gauls, etc.[;]The accompanying sketch is a copy of that accompanying the newspaper article.[;]Copy of covering letter from C. Gardiner of Stroud Museum, to the B.M., dated January 1, 1936: "When I got here some 6 years ago, I found the enclosed cutting. I pursued the bronze and I believe it was bought by a man who behaves badly and exiled himself to Maderia [?]. It is probably locked up in his house here, but though I  have written to him through his lawyer he does not reply. Still, the figure is probably enough to enable you to describe it in the list of English bronzes should you care to do so."
info.publications: An account is given in a cutting from a local (Stroud) newspaper, of uncertain date (but about 1910 or 1911), which account also includes a drawing of the implement. For the relevant extracts, see other side.

info.description: Dimensions: EL 149mm; Wbt 24.2mm; Bfg 29mm; Blp 5.4mm; minBst. 27.1mm; Tsep 8.6mm[;]Wt. 437.2 gms[;]Typology: central raised ridge on blade flanked at top by triangular hollows - not wholly sym.; where preserved fg and st. crests flattened neatly; blade sides neatly shaped to double facet; rounded step-angles and sub-sect. end; shallowness of loop orig. feature; traces of three ribs in sep end - one more prom.; 2 or 3 in rev. sep.[;]Manufacture: dimpling od parts of fg. sides and lower blade - prob. from cg.; curved flow lines/ripples across seps; small stumps of cg. fls on haft sides - fully removed to bevel on bl.; remnant of e. bev. on largest part of bl[;]Condition. While of edge and butt end product of corr. damage - pale green dusty surfaces; 3 fg crests with variable corr. dam - prob only one significantly reduced; loop form lost; gmks prob. all recent[;]Attached Material: yellowy soil matrix in small patches.
info.collection: Hampshire Co. Mus. Service[;]Ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. - private (no. 1)[;]52 Porteous Crescent, Chandlers Ford, Eastleigh, Hampshire

info.surface: Grassy green patina - slightly mottled shades intact over much; corr. lumps and bad pocking scattered - bluey-green
info.description: Dimensions: EL 157.2mm; EWe 48.2mm; EWbt 25.2mm; EBfg. 28.3mm; MinTst. 27mm (+?); T sep 7.5mm; Wt. 445.6 gms[;]Typology: central raised ridge on bl. flanked at top by triang.; diffuse bev at top of sep. hollows and where surviving stop and fg. crests tend to be flattened; bl sides recently double facetted; on sep. floor more rounded in cross section than other - sub. rect. ends with traces of 2 short ribs (left one prom. on one face)[;]Manufacture: little dimpling of fg. sides prob from moulding; stumps of cg. fls on upper sides; fully removed on blade (where gmks mainly longitudinal - poss. recent); remnants of e. bev and hmks on lower blade; some tr. of flow ripples in rev. sep[;]Condition: loop broken in ant.; central part of blade edge probably just corr. chipped - rest were substantially damaged - poss. partly in ant.; part of bl. outline lost through corr.; crests on one face badly damaged - rev. fg. and dec virtually intact; rest of scmks prob. recent.[;]Attached material: yellow brown soil matrix in patches - parts richer ochre-brown
info.collection: Hampshire Co. Museum Service[;]ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. -private (no. 2)

info.patina: Mottled dark to grass green patina over much; rest badly flaked or lumpy corr. to pale bluey - green dry surface.
info.description: Dimensions: EL 156mm; Wbt 24.7mm; Bfg 29.5mm; minBst 27.2mm; Tsep 7.6mm; Wt. 425.1 gms[;]Typology: very slight central ridge on bl.; more prom. and neat on rev. - upper parts flattened and flanked by triang. hollows - not sym.; stop crests flattened - not regular, fg. crests rounded where intact; bl. sides double facetted; one sep. floor more rounded than other; diffuse bev. at top of sep; one sep end with one definite short rib - rev. with prom. one to left. and poss. other(s)[;]Manufacture: Pronounced hammer rippling of bl. faces, less prom. on sides;  no definite e bev - bit diffuse one on rev. face; small porosity hollow in one sep. end; some gmks across bl. e. may be ancient; stump of cg. fl only evid between loop stumps - fully removed elsewhere on intact sides[;]Condition: bl. e. all lost through corr. dam. - poss. previous dam. also; most of break pale green, but one tip grey-green - poss. just p. flaked; presumed loop stumps now just corroded lumps; most of butt lost, little poss. near intact; part of fg. crests little corr. dam; crevice in patina below one top - prob. recent dam.[;]Attached Material: small traces of yello to yellow-brown soil
info.collection: Hampshire Co.. Museum Service[;]ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. - private (no. 3)

info.surface: Grass green patina - much flaked and pitted; dull green with rusty orange staining on rev. bl. face - pitted sur.; elsewhere pale light-green dusty sur., odd lumps pale green corr.; one sep. covered with granular textured blue-green - speckled in odd other places.
info.description: Dimensions: EL 146mm; EWe 48.3mm; EWbt 22.3mm; Bst/fg junction 25mm; Tsep 8.2mm; Wt 379.5 gms[;]Typology: central ribs on near flat bl. faces, flanked by triang. hollow at top; one stop crest dipped in centre and with groove-cum-ridge along it - cast, but also some hammering; fg. crests were prob. rounded; fairly angular, sq. ended sep. one face; rev. sep with more rounded floor and 2 short ribs in end - not symm.; bt. top prob. flat orig.[;]Manufacture: depression between loop stumps - flow or design?; traces of cg. fl. - off central on rev. side, sligt dislocation between parts of the two valves, ? miscast stop (see above); no e. bev. survives[;]Condition: all bl. e. blunt - one bl. tip certainly ancient, rest corr. dam.; fg. crests irreg. due to corr. dam.; loop prob. lost in ant.- but recent rubbing to dull gold on stumps; bt. corr. dam - line poss. little changed.[;]Attached Material: Light yellow-brown soil matrix in pockets.
info.collection: Hampshire Co. Mus. Service[;]ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. - private (no. 4)

info.surface: Grass green patina intact over much of one face, mostly flaked elsewhere to dull green dry sur. with lumpy light blue-green dusty corr.
info.description: Dimensions: EL 146.5mm; EWbt 24.6mm; maxEBfg. 27.4mm; minBst 22.8mm; Tsep 7.5mm; Wt. 384.2 gms[;]Typology: central rib on bl. faces; triang. flanking hollows at top; one stop markedly dipped in centre - not dam. - cg. flaw? possibly was some flattening of narrow fg. crests; rounded bump high across one sep.; this flat undercut end floored with bowed end; rev. sep. with more rounded floor and 2 short ribs in bowed end.[;]Manufacture: traces of cg. ft. as rounded rib or compromised ridge; rev. fl. little off-centre to left; few prob. moulding dimples on sides; depression between deep stumps - cg. flaw? faint hmks near edge - but no defined bevel.[;]Condition: Large bl. corner lost - prob. anc. and corr. dam; rest of e. irreg. from corr. chipping; butt end broken? and corr. dam.; chips in fg. crests - some poss anc., but also corr.; loop presumably broken in ant - one stump rubbed to dull copper; corners of rev. stop crest dam. by corr.; much of rev. dec. lost.[;]Attached Material: light yellowy fawn soil in pockets; remains of the casting of darker rich brown matrix
info.collection: Hampshire Co. Mus. service[;]ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. - private (no. 5)
info.remarks: PIF, AFI; S; SI; CI; SN Jan 79; Source So.A; Sub. Inf. Zillwood, Sept. 78

info.surface: Mottled dark to grass green patina over much; areas flaked/pocked to dirty pale green; some brighter green lumpy corr.; coppery brown sur. at point of e. break; light gold along fg. break - hints of gold along other lower fg.
info.description: Dimensions: EL 147.2mm; EWbt 26.5mm; EBfg 32mm; Bst 18.5mm; Wt. 503.4 gms[;]Typology: Slight  median ridge on bl. faces - descendind from "U" shield shaped emphasised ridge on rev.; prob. near triang. shield on obverse despite corr. dam.; near flat tops to fg. crests; stops are emphasised ridges - dipped in centre; sl. rounded sep angles; orig. crinoline bl. shape[;]Manufacture: flattened stumps of cg. fls. on fg. sides - little lipping; removed to bevel on bl. sides; some hammer rippling of bl. faces and sides - fragment of e. bev. intact; all hmks on fg. sides; moulding dimples on bl. faces and sep.; central moulding depression within either sheild[;]Condition: most broken with corr dam. and pres. anc.; part near orig. line but blunt - corr. c hipped; butt broken off in ant.; virt. whole of one fg. broken off prob.  in ant. but now light gold - ?polished; remaining fgs. little chipped by corr.[;]Attached material: traces fawn soil in sep and in butt end.
info.collection: Hampshire Co. Mus. Service[;]ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. - private (no. 6)
info.remarks: PIF;AFI;S;SI;CI;Rec. SN Dec. 78; Source SbA; Sub Inf. Zillwood Sept 78

info.surface: dark fir green patina over much of one face and sides; few lumps of light green corr., much pocked to sim. colour dusty sur.
info.description: Dimensions: EL 141.2mm; EWst 22.3mm; EBfg 24.5mm; minBst 15mm; Wt. 389.6 gms[;]Typology: rounded medial ridges on bl. faces; descending from 'U' shaped ridge enclosing shallow depression; stop bump dips markedly from fgs to centre where a furrow produces a further notch; 3 ribs in one sep. - traces of at least 2 in rev. sep.; narrow nearly rounded fg. crests.[;]Manufacture: broad low flattened stump of cg. fl on fg. sides - almost a facet; ground awaoy on bl. sides to neat double facet; hint of former e. bev close to present bl. e. - undulations in sep. floors - cg. defects?; few dimples on fg. sides; small [?] on inside of one fg. - defect prob.[;]Condition: all of edge missing - all corroded sur., much pres anc. dam.; all of butt appears broken/corroded, also two reverse fgs much reduced; one abv. fg with notch - light gold colour; gmks in places - mainly recent cleaning[;]Attached Material: Orangey-fawn soil in odd patches
info.collection: Hampshire Co. Mus. Service[;]ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. - private (No. 7)
info.remarks: PIF; AFI; DF S; SI; CI; Rec. SN Jan 79; Source Sb. A; Sub. Inf. Zillwood Sept 78

info.surface: Mottled dark to milky green, scattered limps of brightish green corr. assoc'd with pocks; breaks at edge, butt, and one fg. grey-coloured dry sur.
info.description: Dimensions: EL 136mm; EWe 48.5mm; EWbt 20.9mm; Bfg 29.6mm; Tsep 8.5mm; Bst 13mm; Wt. 372.1 gms[;]Typology: rounded medial ridge on bl faces, with concave flanking on one face, stems from rounded 'V' shield rib joining fg. bases; shield encloses sloped surface below ledge - stop - rounded; three short-thin ribs meet ledge on one face; sep. v. sl. dished with crisp side angles; fg. crests narrow and prob. mainly rounded; neat flattened vert. bars across base of fg. sides[;]Manufacture: no trace of cg. gls - fully removed, and bl. sides forged concave; hmks and dimples on sides and bl. faces, no extant e. bev.[;]Condition: all edge broken - anc. no sign of corr. dam.; butt break pale grey coloured dry sur. - prob. anc. as a small traves of soil embedded, parts of fgs broken - prob. in ant., but also some corr. dam. and modern rubbing - gold glecked; some striction down rev. bl. face - recent cleaning[;]Attached Material: Small traces of yellowy brown soil.
info.collection: Hampshire Co. Mus. Service[;]ex-Zillwood, Mr. M.A. - private (no. 8)
info.remarks: PIF; AFI; DF S; SI; CI; Rec. SN Jan 79; Source Sb A; Sub. Inf. Zillwood sept. 78

info.surface: Black green patina; [occ?] large pittings - light green dry surface. Few light green lumpy corr.; break at e. finely laminated light green structure - soil embedded
info.description: DImensions: EL 150.7mm; EWbt 21.7mm; Bfg 31mm; Bst 15mm; Wt. 413.5 gms[;]Typology: one bl. face with sl. fgs; sl. central rib and one diverging rib - more hints of 2 ribs on left hand side; rev. face with medial ridge only; sl. bumps for stops; shield hollow enclosed only by rounded bev.; sep. floor dipped in middle; fgs with rounded crests[;]Manufacture: Much of cg. fl still emphasised ridge/rib - prob some forging of top, but crests parts lost by corr. , may have been jagged; cg. fl. stump along bl. and also diffuse e. bev. - esp. on one face -  not sharpening - cast; undulation in sep. floor - defect?; small irreg. ridges of metal across top bev.; on inside of one fg.; and perp. to bl. e. - cg. defects; dimples and 'flow' pattern  on sides[;]Condition: [?] e. break dusty corr. sur. - anc. break rather than miscast - on rev. face long straight ? scored groove borders break - marks divide between p. and laminated corr. structure; most of butt grey dry surface with embedded soil - anc. break, one corner copper brown; crest of one fg. badly chipped - prob. mainly recent - [?ring] of corr. layers exposed; fgs. otherwise little dam.; strs. prob. all recent[;]Attached Material: Yellowy-green thin coating matrix in places - soil? fawn soil in a few places.

info.description: Dimensions: EL 135.5mm; EWbl 23.3mm; EBfg 23.3mm; Bst 14mm; Wt. 338.4 gms[;]Typology: travesl of sl. central ridge on bl. faces descending from 'U' shield - sl. emphasised ridge; bump stop dipped in centre, as also sep. floor; stop on rev. was prob. placed lower[;]Manufacture: depression near base of rev. sep - cg. flaw; traces of broad low flattened cg. ft. on fg. sides - prob. fully removed on bl. sides to double facet.[;]Condition: both corners of bl. broken in ant - breaks dustry corr. sur. with soil embedded; main break with 2 facets - gold flecked, recent rubbing?; central part of e. also but blunt; butt end all broken sur.- dusty corr. and soil; all fg. crests dam.- anc. dam and corr. - except tiny stretch of one fg.; much of design detail lost through deterioration.[;]Attached material: yellow-brown soil traces
